Based on the newly gathered information, my revised stance aligns with Option D - "Incision of the duct and removal of calculus." This view supports the idea that for submandibular calculi, particularly those larger than 5mm where conservative treatments fail, surgical intervention involving duct incision and direct manipulation offers a precise means to achieve successful extraction. The literature emphasizes the importance of evaluating stone characteristics (size, location) alongside patient-specific factors before deciding on a course of action. For instance, small (<5mm) and mobile stones benefit greatly from endoscopic approaches whereas larger, immobile stones warrant more aggressive surgical options like duct incision and direct removal. Furthermore, recent advances favor minimally-invasive techniques wherever feasible, highlighting the utility of sialendoscopy even for some large stones ≤7mm. However, when these methods prove insufficient or impractical due to complex anatomy or persistent symptoms despite attempts at conservative management, surgical excision remains a robust fallback strategy. Therefore, while there exists a spectrum of possibilities ranging from least to most invasive, the evidence overwhelmingly points towards incising the duct coupled with manual extraction as a key modality worth prioritizing judiciously according to clinical judgment guided by multimodal assessments inclusive of imaging data and symptomatology reported by patients themselves. Thus, I maintain agreement with earlier conclusions advocating for Option D because it represents an informed middle ground balancing efficacy against safety concerns commonly encountered in everyday practice scenarios involving challenging cases characterized by recalcitrant salivary dysfunction attributed to stubborn calculi resistant to simpler alternatives. \boxed{D}
